Usually I think brunch spots are overhyped or not worth the super long wait, but I woke up early on a Saturday to get to Brenda's at ~8:20am, almost half an hour after they opened to be seated right away!! So keep in mind, this review does not come with the typical brunch wait time attached with it, but I don't even know if that makes any difference when it comes to the food here!! The order: - crawfish beignets: OMG so delicious!!! Clearly these beignets are a little thicker on the outside since they have to hold and house really good portions of crawfish inside, but it's fried perfectly, stuffed with goodness, and topped with spices that just make every bite SO DANG GOOD. - pork belly & cheesy grits: what I'm about to say is gonna sound like I'm over exaggerating but I kid you not, my eyes watered with my first bite. I'm a person that loves to love food and this first bite literally brought me tears of joy!!! The bf kinda laughed at first because of my drama, but when he tried a bite, he agreed. It is GOOD. - croque monsieur (& fried egg): the bread. The ham. The cheese. The egg. It's the perfect blend of flavors and textures here. Again, idk what the heck was up with that Saturday morning, but every first bite was just so good!! Definitely worth a try if you're ever in SF and looking for some Cajun brunch! But I'd recommend going early if you don't like to wait :)

I am definitely not a Soul Food Expert and what qualifies to be such great Soul Food that's for sure haha. But can I just say, this place hit the spot??!! Sadly... the closest soul food I've ever gotten to try was Hard Knox. Brenda's for damn sure set the bar compared to Hard Knox... FOR. SURE. lol Coming to Brenda's, especially during the weekends, do prepare for the worst of taming your hanger or patience because there can be quiet a long line and/or a long wait. I find this place to be a hidden, yet straightforward gem that stands out. I came here with my friends after volunteering for Nike Women's Marathon and I definitely worked up an appetite. Although it was packed and there was a wait, it ended up being worth it because the food was B O M B!!!! I ordered the french toast and I was served this decent long plate that had a good amount of slices of french toast sprinkled with powdered sugar and a small cup of warm syrup on the side!! These french toasts look simple but MAN they are so yummy. My friend had ordered the fried chicken and that was so freakin yummy as well. Crispy skin on the outside, tender white meat on the inside, such pure heaven. Next time I come here, I am really looking forward to trying the shrimp and grits. Brenda's is definitely a $$ restaurant, however, it is worth it.

I've lived in the Bay Area most of my life and I've only ever really heard two things about Brenda's: 1) It is sooo good. Try the _______ (e.g., shrimp & grits, chicken, beignets, etc.). 2) Get there early because the line is crazy! I'm really grateful that my coworker and I ended up getting into the city at around 4 PM after a morning hike to Tomales Point which, by the way, is absolutely gorgeous and chock full of elk during what I can only assume is their mating season. Grateful because there was absolutely no line and their chalkboard was EMP-TY. Parking was also pretty easy and we got a metered spot right across the street. Our server, Bianca, was friendly and engaging and our order came out quite quickly. I was fresh from a hike and feeling lightheaded and hungry so I ordered two entrees and a beignet flight. If i'm honest, though, I probably would have ordered two entrees even if I hadn't gone on a hike just so I could try everything! I still need to go back to try their red beans and rice... buttermilk fried chicken - 14.75 shrimp and grits - 17 flight beignets - 12 I am, however, cursed with having greedier eyes that want more than my stomach can actually hold... comfortably that is. I polished off the shrimp and grits and still dream off that delightful smoky, slightly spicy flavor. I ended up having to wave the white dinner napkin flag when it came to the fried chicken and all the other beignets save the plain one in all its tempting, doughy, powdered glory. I can't comment on either the chicken or the rest of the beignets because they magically disappeared from the refrigerator at home that night... I guess I just need to visit Brenda's again!

My friend and I arrived around 8:30am and we were seated almost immediately. We ordered our drinks and food, and I kid you not, everything was on our table within 7 mins of ordering. We enjoyed our breakfast a lot! I had the pulled pork eggs benedict, my friend had the gumbo and we shared the flight of beignets. We were full halfway into eating our food because everything was so rich. The only thing I didn't like was the coffee. It tasted like it was the end of the coffee pot... When we were leaving around 9:20-ish am, the waitlist was long and there were a lot of people waiting. I'm glad we got there early because I know this place can get super packed.

We arrived at 8:15am and only a few tables were occupied. By the time we left, about an hour later, there was a line out the door already. Lol. I left with a tiny bit of smugness cause I didn't have to stand in line, but yes I woke up damn early for it. I came here for the beignets that I've seen on Yelp photos, but I honestly had to say that those were the least of everything we ordered. Don't get me wrong, they're great. But the other dishes were just splendid. The shrimp and grits were soo goood. The grits were soft and fluffy, not at all gritty. They were a hit with everyone. And the eggs benedict was dainty and wonderful. Eggs poached to perfection and oozing gold. The hash was pretty average. Hot chocolates are hard to mess up.. and the crawfish beignets were actually pretty big in size. The crawfish filling had a very interesting flavor and worth the try, but the beignet dough probably was not a breakfast thing... It was on the oily and donuty / snacky side. So we gouged out all the crawfish and left half a shell of the beignet left on the table. Pretty pricey for breakfast but it was worth the try. Honestly it was good overall, but to me it's more of a bucket list checked off kind of thing. When I come visit SF again, I'd probably go explore something else, won't necessarily come back for this. Especially with the line.....

If you are in the Bay Area and longing for the NOLA flavor, this just might be the spot for you. We began with the beignet flights and some cocktails. The beignets were light. The plain and crawfish were the table favs. Spiked pink lemonade was the table choice, but proceed with caution, as it will have you walking with a limp. The entrees were as follows: Shrimp and grits: The base had too much of a tomato flavor. Not a fan of the tomato gravy. The burger: The burger created a perfect balance of sweet and savory with the goat cheese and sweet pickles. Very flavorful and perfectly balanced. Spicy pasta: This was a VERY delicious dish. It had fresh seafood and was perfectly seasoned. Etouffee: The etouffee was another well received dish. It was full of chicken. It was a little watery for me, but the flavor was there. All in all we had phenomenal service and dynamic drinks. Although I would not recommend the shrimp and grits, the drinks and other dishes were a solid choice. Not the BEST neighborhood so be mindful.

    I've lived in the Bay Area most of my life and I've only ever really heard two things about Brenda's:

    1) It is sooo good.  Try the _______ (e.g., shrimp & grits, chicken, beignets, etc.).
    2) Get there early because the line is crazy!

    I'm really grateful that my coworker and I ended up getting into the city at around 4 PM after a morning hike to Tomales Point which, by the way, is absolutely gorgeous and chock full of elk during what I can only assume is their mating season.  Grateful because there was absolutely no line and their chalkboard was EMP-TY.  Parking was also pretty easy and we got a metered spot right across the street.  

    Our server, Bianca, was friendly and engaging and our order came out quite quickly.  I was fresh from a hike and feeling lightheaded and hungry so I ordered two entrees and a beignet flight.  If i'm honest, though, I probably would have ordered two entrees even if I hadn't gone on a hike just so I could try everything!  I still need to go back to try their red beans and rice...

    buttermilk fried chicken - 14.75
    shrimp and grits - 17
    flight beignets - 12

    I am, however, cursed with having greedier eyes that want more than my stomach can actually hold... comfortably that is.  I polished off the shrimp and grits and still dream off that delightful smoky, slightly spicy flavor.  I ended up having to wave the white dinner napkin flag when it came to the fried chicken and all the other beignets save the plain one in all its tempting, doughy, powdered glory.  

    I can't comment on either the chicken or the rest of the beignets because they magically disappeared from the refrigerator at home that night... I guess I just need to visit Brenda's again!

    If you are in the Bay Area and longing for the NOLA flavor, this just might be the spot for you. We began with the beignet flights and some cocktails. The beignets were light. The plain and crawfish were the table favs. Spiked pink lemonade was the table choice, but proceed with caution, as it will have you walking with a limp. The entrees were as follows:
    Shrimp and grits: The base had too much of a tomato flavor. Not a fan of the tomato gravy.
    The burger: The burger created a perfect balance of sweet and savory with the goat cheese and sweet pickles. Very flavorful and perfectly balanced.
    Spicy pasta: This was a VERY delicious dish. It had fresh seafood and was perfectly seasoned.
    Etouffee: The etouffee was another well received dish.  It was full of chicken. It was a little watery for me, but the flavor was there.
    All in all we had phenomenal service and dynamic drinks. Although I would not recommend the shrimp and grits, the drinks and other dishes were a solid choice. Not the BEST neighborhood so be mindful.

    One of the best brunches I've had in the city. We went on a Sunday at 1PM and the wait was a little over an hour for a table for 3. The place is pretty crowded but service was great and we got our food quickly.

    We started off with a flight of beignets - plain, Ghirardelli chocolate, crawfish, and apple. They are HUGE and you can definitely split a flight between 2-3 people. The coffee is also really tasty.

    so i have been trying to come to brenda's for quite some time now. but with every visit i just can't seem to ever make it out here. the long lines get pretty discouraging.

    how it's worked:
    Write your name on their chalkboard to the right to reserve a table. They only seat you when your whole party is present. Food comes out quickly. Great presentation and service!

    Ordered:
    *Crawfish beignets - sooo good!  the reviews on yelp is accurate. i didn't even bother ordering the sampler beignets. I've only ever tried regular beignets with powdered sugar so this was a very nice surprise! be prepared to have your mouth and fingers a bit red but it comes out and its so worth the redness.
    *Fried chicken Benedict with grits- never been a fan of grits and I am still not fond of it. however, the Fried chicken Benedict was pretty delicious. Especially with that sauce! Flavorful without needing to add any hot sauce. so perfect the way it is!

    would i:
    I would totally come back! Everything was amazingly tasty! i totally would recommend fellow yelpers and foodies to try out brenda's! the trick is to come early. saw a lot of folks with their luggage/carry ons so they must've came straight from the airport. that goes to show you how good brenda's is.  you won't have any regrets with dining here.

    Tips:
    *High chair available
    *Cash & credit card accepted
    *Restroom available.
    *Indoor seating only.
    *alcohol served
